5–1442","1440–1486":"1440–1486","1390–1464":"1390–1464","1405–1467":"1405–1467","Apr 1419":"april 1419","1440":"1440","1480":"1480","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","Abt. 1442":"circa 1442","1405":"1405","Tyled Hall, Latchingdon, Essex, England":"Latchingdon, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tyle Hall, Latchingdon, Essex, England":"Latchingdon, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1420–1480":"1420–1480","1420–1475":"1420–1475","1435–Female":"1435–Deceased","1415–1442":"1415–1442","1440–1486":"1440–1486","1390–1464":"1390–1464","1405–1467":"1405–1467","Apr 1419":"April 1419","1440":"1440","1480":"1480","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","Abt. 1442":"about 1442","1405":"1405","Tyled Hall, Latchingdon, Essex, England":"Latchingdon, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Tyle Hall, Latchingdon, Essex, England":"Latchingdon, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osbern</i>, partly from late Old English <i>Ōsbern</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Ásbiǫrn</i> (from <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>biǫrn</i> ‘bear’), but more usually from Norman use of the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Ōsbern</i>. <i>Osbern</i> was often treated as an alternative form of <i>Osbert</i>. For pet forms see   Hoskin   and   Opie  . The surname has also been established in Ireland (Waterford, Tipperary) since the mid 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbon","meanings":["English (Sussex): variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborne","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Oborne in Dorset. The placename derives from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’.","possibly from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]},{"name":"Orsburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbun","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Hoskin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osekin</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a pet form of Anglo-Norman French names beginning with <i>Os-</i> (particularly <i>Osbert</i>, as well as <i>Osbern</i>, and <i>Osmund</i>) + the Flemish diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. All three personal names were current in medieval Cornwall or Devon; see   Osborne  ,   Osmond  , and   Opie   (a pet form of <i>Osbert</i>). Old English <i>Ōsbeorn</i>, <i>Ōsbeohrt</i>, and <i>Ōsmund</i> may also have contributed in a minor way to Middle English usage; Middle English   Oswald   is another possible source, but the name was very rare in the late 14th century. For the excrescent initial <i>H-</i>, compare   Herrick  ."]},{"name":"Osborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Orsborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborn","meanings":["English (Somerset): habitational name chiefly from Oborne in Dorset, or perhaps occasionally from Howbourne Farm in Hadlow Down, Sussex, Woburn in Bedfordshire, Woburn Park in Surrey, or Wooburn in Buckinghamshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’, except Wooburn in Buckinghamshire, which is of uncertain etymology.","English (of Norman origin): perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Kent","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from the English county. This is probably named with a Celtic word meaning ‘border’. Use as a given name is of recent origin, but it is now quite popular. It may in part be seen as a short form of   Kenton ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Kent Osborne was born in 1420, in Essex, England, his father, Sir William Kent Osborne, was 30 and his mother, Joan Sittingbourne, was 15. He married Elizabeth Essex in 1440, in Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1480, in Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1420–1480":"1420–1480","1420–1475":"1420–1475","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1415–1442":"1415–1442","1440–1486":"1440–1486","1390